In the case of Cuthbert’s Life it cannot, Ι think, be said that Bede has bettered his original. He has improved the Latinity no doubt, and made the Whole thing run more smoothly. In fact he seems to take delight in altering the language for the mere sake of alteration, While keep· ing closely to the sense. But he has obliterated many interesting details of time ,and place ¹, he shows a marked tendency to exaggerate the ascetic and miraculous ele- ment, he amplifies the narrative With rhetorical matter which can only be called padding 2, inserts as facts ex- planations of his own3, and has greatly spoiled one beautiful anecdote4.
